folder: Washington Square North & 5th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
Washington Arch, Washington Square North, at Fifth Avenue, a night view looking north from the park.
The Washington Arch, built in 1890 to commemorate the inauguration of President Washington in New York, is shown illuminated by electric lights at the time of the Hudson-Fulton Centenary celebration.

1909.

August Loeffler, from P. L. Sperr Collection.

folder: Washington Square North & 5th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
14-22 Washington Square North, looking west from Fifth Avenue. These fine old residences antedate the Civil War. In front of No. 15 is the spot where Sandy Hill Road, a part of which has become Greenwich Avenue and another part of which has become Astor Place, crossed the main branch of Minetta Creek in the 18th Century. It is possible that this was the crossing at which the old "Kissing Bridge" was located. February 24, 1922.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

folder: 5th Avenue and Washington Square, Manhattan, N.Y.
text:
Celebrations, Parades, and Municipal Events: Three views of National Guard and Naval Reserve units marching northward on Fifth Avenue from Washington Square. These contingents have just passed W. 10th Street (in views 1 and 2), at the N. W. corner of which appears a portion of the Church of the Ascension. View 3 is photographed in the opposite direction. At the left is the 1st Presbyterian Church occupying the avenue frontage from 11th to 12th Streets. Note the new 8 story Mac Millan and Co. Building under construction at the N. W. corner of 12th Street.

1924
Views 1,2,3

folder: Washington Square & 5th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
Washington Square (Park): The Washington Memorial Arch viewing northward and up Fifth Avenue. Buildings on the left and right of same, are respectively the Rhinelander and Sailor's Snug Harbor holdings, fronting on the north side of Washington Square North. Note that at this date the huge apartment house (No 1 Fifth Avenue) has not been erected and that the old Hotel Brevoort still stands.

June 1925

text:
Fifth Aveue, west side, between Washington Square North and West 8th Street, showing the 2 story residence of Chancellor Chase of N.Y.U. This is to the rear of the rebuilt Rhinelander apartment building at the N.W. corner of W.S. North and the Avenue. To the right are three 4 story residences bearing No's 4, 6 & 8 Fifth Avenue. folder: Washington Square & 5th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
Washington Square Park:

Washington Arch, Washington Square, seen from the north so as to show the Judson Memorial Baptist Church (1892) framed in the archway, and the fountain in the center of the park. The church stands on the S.W. corner of Thompson Street and Washington Square South (4th Street).

This arch was built around 1890; the wooden one designed by Stanford White for the Centenary of President Washington's inauguration, in 1889, was so well liked that it was decided to erect a permanent arch of stone, which White also designed.

May 5, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan: Washington Square - 5th Avenue

folder: 5th Avenue & Washington Square, Manhattan, NY
text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, north from Washington Square, seen through Washington Arch. The day on which this exposure was made was gratifyingly clear. The Empire State Building, the tallest building in the world, at 34th Street, stands out well, and even 500 Fifth Avenue, at the N.W. corner of 42nd Street, can be plainly discerned.

July 17, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - Washington Square

folder: Washington Square South & 5th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Washington Square Park, eastern half, seen across the Square from a building near the S.W. corner.
This view is almost straight east on Washington Square South (4th Street), showing the Judson Memorial Church (1892) and the clearing made about 1927 on the S.E. corner of Thompson Street.
August 1, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, but a little further to the north, showing part of the new One Fifth Avenue apartment hotel (1926), and not showing Washington Square South.
The apartment building on the N.E. corner of University and Waverly Places was erected in 1929. Compare both these views with Ewing Galloway's picture taken about 1925.
August 1, 1935.
